TY  - JOUR
T1  - Market Microstructure and Incentives to Invest
AU  - Spulber, Daniel F.
Y1  - 2002/04/01
PY  - 2002
DA  - 2002/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/338749
DO  - 10.1086/338749
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 352
EP  - 381
VL  - 110
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Market organization significantly affects total output and incentives for firms to invest. I compare three types of market organization. In a market with search and random matching, total output is excessive and there are incentives for inefficient underinvestment. In a market with a monopoly dealer, total output is insufficient and underinvestment also occurs. Competition between the search market and the dealer market improves incentives to invest, and competition between dealers yields efficient total output and investment. This suggests that additional entry of wholesalers and other interbusiness dealers should stimulate aggregate business investment.
AB  - Market organization significantly affects total output and incentives for firms to invest. I compare three types of market organization. In a market with search and random matching, total output is excessive and there are incentives for inefficient underinvestment. In a market with a monopoly dealer, total output is insufficient and underinvestment also occurs. Competition between the search market and the dealer market improves incentives to invest, and competition between dealers yields efficient total output and investment. This suggests that additional entry of wholesalers and other interbusiness dealers should stimulate aggregate business investment.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/338749
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/338749
Y2  - 2024/03/19
